    <title type="html"><![CDATA[A Sound of Thunder]]></title>
    <link href="http://antulik.com/blog/2011/11/04/a-sound-of-thunder/"/>
    <updated>2011-11-04T16:35:00+04:00</updated>
    <id>http://antulik.com/blog/2011/11/04/a-sound-of-thunder</id>
    <content type="html"><![CDATA[<p> <strong>“A Sound of Thunder”</strong> is a <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Science_fiction" title="Science fiction">science fiction</a> <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Short_story" title="Short story">short story</a> by <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ray_Bradbury" title="Ray Bradbury">Ray Bradbury</a>, first published in _ <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Collier%27s" title="Collier's">Collier’s</a>_ magazine in <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1952_in_literature" title="1952 in literature">1952</a>. As of 1984 it was the most re-published <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Science_fiction" title="Science fiction">science fiction</a> story up to the present time.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-0"><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/A_Sound_of_Thunder#cite_note-0"><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> It is based on the concept of the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Butterfly_effect" title="Butterfly effect">butterfly effect</a>, as well as, perhaps, the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Snowball_effect" title="Snowball effect">snowball effect</a>.<br/>
&ndash; <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/A_Sound_of_Thunder">Wikipedia</a></p>
